“Carbapenem-resistant Enterobacteriaceae are nightmare bacteria.”
— Tom Frieden, former CDC Director

Carbapenemase-producing bacteria are critical public health threats, with infection mortality rates upwards of ~50%.
Bacteria have evolved these enzymes that inactivate carbapenems, often considered our last-line antibiotics.

As a small PhD side project, I wanted to see whether protein language models could help map the mutational landscape of carbapenemases.

I trained a neural network classifier on ESM-2 protein embeddings to distinguish class A carbapenemases from closely related non-carbapenemase β-lactamases, then performed exhaustive in-silico mutagenesis of KPC-4.

By scoring every possible amino-acid substitution, the model highlights mutations predicted to disrupt or preserve carbapenemase-associated sequence features.

The result is a complete mutation landscape of KPC-4, revealing which residues could present as future sequence variants or functional carbapenemase mutation trajectories.

Key pieces of the workflow:

• Sequence downloads from CARD
• Protein language model embeddings (ESM-2)
• Neural network classifier (PyTorch)
• Exhaustive mutation scanning
• Structural visualization with ESMFold
• Embedding analysis (UMAP)

All code and outputs are available in the repository.

This is a demonstration that protein language model embeddings may be used to map functional mutation landscapes in priority antibiotic resistance genes.

